deck: British publisher that was set up to continue publication of Redfox
description:
The creator of Redfox (known under the pseudonym of simply "Fox") initially had a deal with the publisher Harrier to produce a series of eight issues of the comic (this ended up being extended to 10 to allow the story arc to finish). Finding at the end of the agreement that he still had more that he wanted to do with the character he and Christina Bell set up Valkyrie Press to continue publication themselves.

Later Valkyrie Press also decided to re-publish and complete Bryan Talbot's The Adventures of Luther Arkwright, a British comic strip that had had a turbulent publishing history over the previous decade.

The company came to an abrupt end in 1989 when Chris Bell left to have a baby.
name: Valkyrie Press

deck: As of June 2013 Flint Comix is going into its fifth year of giving away free original content as well as syndicated material. The latest cover of Flint Comix was drawn by the legendary George Perez and was virtually out of supply as soon as it hit the stands.  Randy Zimmerman one of the original founders of Arrow Comics and Ted Valley head of Vertigo theatrics started this paper as an experimetn in entertainment to the natives of Flint and Genesee county as well as the surrounding areas.
description:
Flint Comix and Entertainment - is a locally owned and distributed comics and entertainment paper in Michigan in the Flint/ Genesee County region. They have over 15,000 papers distributed monthly and contain such goodies as the King Features syndicated James Bond, Judge Dredd, and pulp era Flash Gordon. Among its pages you'll find an editorial from the Mayor of Flint, Comic goodness from creators like Levi Krause, Gemma Keech, Layne and Peri Toth and many more.

Flint Comix and Entertainment is a free to readers comics and entertainment paper based around Flint Michigan. They carry comics of all genres and types as long as it's quality driven and "family friendly". Our primary goal is to supply the area access to sequential art and blue collar style entertainment in all its forms, with a unique perspective and focus on the local area and talent. They now have over 5 years worth of publishing history under our belt, and an incredibly loyal, large local readership that easily surpasses our print run and is constantly growing along with us.

Flint Comix is the brainchild of graphic artist/writer and self publisher Randy Zimmerman (Co-Founder of Arrow Comix, and Owner of Zimm Graphix), and Ted Valley (owner of Vertigo Theatrics), and is distributed from well over 300 different points in the Flint Area. You will find copies in Family Restaurants, Laundromats, Public Libraries, Book Stores, Comic Shops, Doughnut Shops, and many, many other places. Additionally we have a number of newsstand outside vendor boxes in the area making the paper available to their readers as well.

Flint Comix features sequential art (comics) from almost every source available, they print single panel gag cartoons, comic strips (funny as well as dramatic), comic book style stories of all forms. Flint Comix also carries articles of local entertainment interest and information, a monthly astrology column, a "random rant" and a monthly column featuring the musings of professional comedians and an editorial by Flint's Mayor (currently Dayne Walling).

  • Ted Valley - Publisher
  • Randy Zimmerman - Editor-in-Chief
  • Jaque Valley - CFO
  • Amanda Valley - Copy Editor
  • Zimm Graphix - Layout Services
name: Flint Comix & Entertainment

deck: Home of the first Frence Superhero
description:
This publishing company which was started in 1940 mainly to published comics illustrated or written by Pierre Mouchot who was known by the name Chott, had to stop during the Nazi occupation, Starting again in 1946 with the adventures of Phantom inspired Fantax it was banned by the French government because of its violent content, so that issues 5 and 6 were text without art, he later was able to restart both Fantax and a number of other comics, publishing them throughout the 50s in pocket sized editions with black & white interiors.

In 1960 the government once again charged his comics with violence, this time when taken down in 1961 they did not return as Mouchot had gone broke and died just a few years later.
name: Éditions Pierre Mouchot
